        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(control-ui): WebSocket connects to wrong gateway when two share an origin",
        "body": "Closes #97636\n\n## What Problem This Solves\n\nFixes an issue where users with two OpenClaw Gateways served under different basePaths on the same origin (e.g. `https://example.com/gateway-a/` and `https://example.com/gateway-b/`) would find that Gateway B's WebSocket connected to Gateway A's backend. The symptom is deterministic: any gateway page that has no saved settings of its own picks up the most-recently-saved sibling gateway's URL and opens its WebSocket there instead.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\n`persistSettings` was writing every save to two keys: a URL-scoped key (`openclaw.control.settings.v1:wss://…/gateway-a`) and the legacy unscoped key (`openclaw.control.settings.v1`). `loadSettings` fell back to the unscoped key when the scoped key was absent. Because all gateways on the same origin share `localStorage`, the unscoped key always contained the URL of whichever gateway last saved—making the fallback read a cross-gateway pollutant.\n\nTwo focused changes fix this:\n\n1. **`loadSettings`**: before accepting a fallback from the unscoped key, compare the stored `gatewayUrl`'s basePath scope against the page-derived URL. Reject the fallback when scopes differ so a sibling's settings are never adopted.\n2. **`persistSettings`**: stop writing to the legacy unscoped key. Each gateway already writes a URL-scoped key; the unscoped write served only as a pollution vector.\n\n## User Impact\n\nOperators serving multiple gateways under one origin with path-based routing will no longer see a gateway page connect its WebSocket to a sibling gateway's backend. Each gateway page now derives its connection URL exclusively from its own basePath, regardless of which other gateways have been opened in the same browser profile.\n\n## Evidence\n\nTwo new unit tests in `storage.node.test.ts` cover the regression and the write-side fix:\n\n```\n✓ does not adopt the gateway URL from a sibling gateway sharing the same origin\n✓ does not write to the legacy unscoped settings key when saving\n```\n\nFull suite result (22/22):\n\n```\nTest Files  1 passed (1)\n     Tests  22 passed (22)\n  Duration  1.87s\n```\n\nThe existing \"ignores and scrubs legacy persisted tokens\" test is updated to use a matching basePath pathname (the real legacy-migration scenario) so it continues to verify token scrubbing without relying on the now-rejected cross-basePath fallback.\n\n_AI-assisted (Claude Sonnet, logic verified and tests written by author)_",
